  <section class="otto-card">
    <h2 class="otto-h2">Hooks</h2>
    <p>OTTO Gateway processes every request through a configurable hook chain. The default chain is enabled out-of-the-box; narrow it via the <code>ENABLED_HOOKS</code> env var (comma-separated allowlist; empty value = all hooks active).</p>

    <h3 class="otto-h3">Default hook chain</h3>
    <div class="otto-docs-table-scroll">
      <table class="otto-table otto-docs-flags-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th scope="col">Hook</th><th scope="col">Kind</th><th scope="col">Default</th><th scope="col">Purpose</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><code>RequestIDHook</code></td><td>Pre</td><td>enabled</td><td>Assigns a unique request ID propagated through structured logs and downstream worker headers.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>AuthHook</code></td><td>Pre</td><td>enabled</td><td>Enforces bearer-token (<code>AUTH_TOKEN</code>) + IP-allowlist (<code>ALLOWED_IPS</code>) when configured. No-op when both are empty (Node parity).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>PIIRedactionHook</code></td><td>Pre,Post</td><td>enabled</td><td>Detects and redacts PII in inbound prompts before they reach the upstream worker (Pre). The default mode is <code>encrypt</code>: detected matches become <code>[PII:Entity:base64url(...)]</code> AES-256-GCM tokens before the worker sees them, and the Post hook decrypts those tokens back to plaintext before the client sees the response (transparent round-trip). Set <code>PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=false</code> to opt out (the hook stays in the chain but does no work).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><code>LoggingHook</code></td><td>Pre,Post</td><td>enabled</td><td>Emits structured request/response log entries (slog JSON). The same instance runs as the last Pre hook and the only Post hook, bridging timings via an internal request-ID map.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3 class="otto-h3">PII redaction</h3>
    <p>PIIRedactionHook is dual-natured: it runs Pre (third in the chain, after RequestID and Auth) so redacted prompts never reach the upstream worker, and Post (after the worker's response) so encrypt-mode tokens can be decrypted back to plaintext before the client sees the response. <strong>It is on by default with <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE=encrypt</code> — the worker never sees plaintext PII unless the operator explicitly opts out via <code>PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=false</code>.</strong></p>
    <p>Recognizer set: 13 regex recognizers (<code>Email</code>, <code>IPv4</code>, <code>IPv6</code>, <code>SSN</code>, <code>CreditCard</code>, <code>USPhone</code>, <code>SIP_URI</code>, <code>IMEI</code>, <code>IMSI</code>, <code>MSISDN</code>, <code>MAC_ADDRESS</code>, <code>COORDINATES</code>, <code>SITE</code>) plus 2 NER recognizers from <code>jdkato/prose/v2</code> (<code>PERSON</code>, <code>LOCATION</code>) when <code>PII_NER_ENABLED=true</code>. Context-anchored recognizers (<code>IMEI</code>, <code>IMSI</code>, <code>MSISDN</code>, <code>SITE</code>) require a recognizer-specific keyword within ±50 bytes of the match.</p>

    <dl class="otto-about-dl">
      <dt><code>PII_REDACTION_ENABLED</code></dt><dd>default <code>true</code> — master switch. Set to <code>false</code> to keep the hook in the chain but inert (operator opt-out).</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_REDACTION_MODE</code></dt><dd>default <code>encrypt</code> — one of <code>replace</code> (numbered sentinel per match), <code>mask</code> (partial obfuscation), <code>hash</code> (HMAC-keyed correlation token), <code>drop</code> (matched substring removed entirely), <code>encrypt</code> (AES-256-GCM round-trip — request encrypted, response decrypted by the Post hook before the client sees it).</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_NER_ENABLED</code></dt><dd>default <code>true</code> — master switch for the prose-based PERSON/LOCATION recognizer. When <code>true</code>, the bundled averaged-perceptron model lazy-loads on first request. Set to <code>false</code> to skip the runtime tokenizer/tagger allocation (the ~7 MB binary impact is baked into the build either way). English-only; accuracy is decent on common Western names and major place names but weaker on Asian / multilingual names.</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_ENABLED_ENTITIES</code></dt><dd>default empty (all registered recognizers active) — comma-separated allowlist from <code>Email,IPv4,IPv6,SSN,CreditCard,USPhone,SIP_URI,IMEI,IMSI,MSISDN,MAC_ADDRESS,COORDINATES,SITE,PERSON,LOCATION</code>. <code>PERSON</code> and <code>LOCATION</code> require <code>PII_NER_ENABLED=true</code> to actually fire.</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_ENTITY_ACTIONS</code></dt><dd>default empty — per-entity action override map. Shape: <code>Entity:action,Entity:action,…</code> (e.g. <code>Email:encrypt,SSN:drop,PERSON:mask</code>). Listed entities use the named action; unlisted entities fall back to <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE</code>. Allowed actions: <code>replace</code>, <code>mask</code>, <code>hash</code>, <code>drop</code>, <code>encrypt</code>. Unknown entity name or action ⇒ boot error.</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_HASH_KEY</code></dt><dd>auto-minted by <code>otto-gw init</code> — REQUIRED when <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE=hash</code> (boot error otherwise). HMAC-SHA256 key. Rotating it invalidates prior session correlation tokens.</dd>
      <dt><code>PII_ENCRYPT_KEY</code></dt><dd>auto-minted by <code>otto-gw init</code> — REQUIRED when encrypt is active anywhere (the default <code>PII_REDACTION_MODE=encrypt</code>, OR any <code>PII_ENTITY_ACTIONS</code> entry of the form <code>Entity:encrypt</code>); boot error otherwise, naming the env var in the fatal log. Any non-empty string; the gateway derives a 32-byte AES-256-GCM key via SHA-256 at boot. <code>--regenerate-secrets</code> rotates this alongside <code>AUTH_TOKEN</code> and <code>PII_HASH_KEY</code>. Rotating invalidates every prior encrypted token (decrypt-on-response will fail) — treat as a breaking change for any in-flight round-tripping conversation. Streaming is auto-disabled when encrypt is active (the Pre hook flips <code>Stream=false</code> and adapters re-route to the aggregated path).</dd>
    </dl>

    <p>Detected PII is replaced with bracketed sentinels like <code>[EMAIL_1]</code>, <code>[PHONE_2]</code>, <code>[EMAIL:h-abc12345]</code> (hash mode), or <code>[PII:EMAIL:base64url(...)]</code> (encrypt mode, the default). Square brackets are deliberate — angle-bracketed sentinels like <code>&lt;EMAIL_1&gt;</code> caused kiro-cli to treat them as opening XML tags (see fix 260531-pt8).</p>

    <h3 class="otto-h3">Examples</h3>
    <pre class="otto-code-block"># Default config — PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=true, PII_REDACTION_MODE=encrypt,
# PII_NER_ENABLED=true, PII_ENCRYPT_KEY auto-minted at install:
#   request:  "Email a@b.com — John Smith called"
#   → worker: "Email [PII:EMAIL:base64url(...)] — [PII:PERSON:base64url(...)] called"
#   response: "Tell [PII:PERSON:base64url(...)] I got [PII:EMAIL:base64url(...)]"
#   → client: "Tell John Smith I got a@b.com"
# Streaming auto-disabled in encrypt mode; adapters re-route to aggregated path.</pre>
    <pre class="otto-code-block">PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=true
PII_REDACTION_MODE=replace
# Numbered sentinels per match per entity:
#   "Email me at a@b.com or c@d.com"
#   → "Email me at [EMAIL_1] or [EMAIL_2]"</pre>
    <pre class="otto-code-block">PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=true
PII_REDACTION_MODE=hash
PII_HASH_KEY=&lt;32+ random bytes, hex or base64&gt;
PII_ENABLED_ENTITIES=Email,SSN
# Same value → same hash sentinel within a key lifetime (correlation
# across requests without leaking the underlying PII):
#   "a@b.com … a@b.com" → "[EMAIL:h-9f3a2c1d] … [EMAIL:h-9f3a2c1d]"</pre>
    <pre class="otto-code-block"># Per-entity action mix — global encrypt, but mask PERSON for human readability
# in audit logs and drop LOCATION entirely from the worker's view:
PII_REDACTION_ENABLED=true
PII_REDACTION_MODE=encrypt
PII_ENCRYPT_KEY=&lt;auto-minted; rotate via --regenerate-secrets&gt;
PII_NER_ENABLED=true
PII_ENTITY_ACTIONS=PERSON:mask,LOCATION:drop</pre>

    <p><strong>SENSITIVE:</strong> <code>CHAT_TRACE=true</code> writes raw prompts to <code>CHAT_TRACE_FILE</code> <em>before</em> PIIRedactionHook runs. When chat-trace is on, the on-disk file contains unredacted PII — this is why the About page surfaces a SENSITIVE badge whenever <code>CHAT_TRACE=true</code>. Turn off in production unless intentionally debugging a request shape.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="otto-card">
    <h2 class="otto-h2">Basic admin usage</h2>
    <ul class="otto-docs-bullets">
      <li><strong>Status pill</strong> — green = healthy (pool ready + at least one slot idle), amber = degraded (KIRO_CMD missing or pool starving), red = down (no slots, no recovery in flight).</li>
      <li><strong>Pool slots</strong> — one card per warm kiro-cli subprocess; idle (yellow), busy (purple), or terminated (red) with last-error context.</li>
      <li><strong>Active sessions</strong> — stateful conversation sessions per the session registry; idle &gt; <code>SESSION_TTL_MS</code> are reaped on the next tick.</li>
      <li><strong>Log tail</strong> — pick a source from the dropdown, stream SSE-delivered lines into the table. Use the search box for client-side <code>dataset.raw</code> grep.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="otto-card">
    <h2 class="otto-h2">Troubleshooting</h2>
    <ul class="otto-docs-bullets">
      <li><strong>Status shows degraded</strong> — usually <code>KIRO_CMD</code> is unset or not on <code>$PATH</code>. Check the Upstream Worker card on <a href="/admin/about">About</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>Status shows down</strong> — all pool slots terminated. Inspect the Log tail filtered on <code>pool.acquire</code> / <code>pool.recover</code> for the underlying spawn or ACP error.</li>
      <li><strong>Requests hang for ~120s then time out</strong> — server-side stream-idle watchdog is disabled (<code>STREAM_IDLE_TIMEOUT_SEC=0</code>) and the upstream stalled silently. Re-enable the watchdog (default 30s) and retry.</li>
      <li><strong>"chat trace enabled" warning at startup</strong> — <code>CHAT_TRACE=true</code> writes raw prompts to disk at the path shown in <em>Files &amp; paths</em>. Turn off in production unless intentionally debugging.</li>
      <li><strong>Where do logs go?</strong> — structured slog JSON to stdout / stderr by default; set <code>LOG_FILE</code> for a rotated on-disk copy.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</main>{{end}}
